The relations between Prosper Rating and other features¶

by Mohammed Nasser¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation , I will demonstrate the relationship between the Prosper Rating and some of the other aspects in this data set.

Dataset Overview¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. [Loan Data Last updated 03/11/2014] .

The number of persons who choose each prosper rating type¶

Several people are taking a medium amount of risk when making investments or taking out loans.

the number of people with each Income Range across all Prosper Rating types¶

People with a salary of 50,000 to 75,000 likely to take modest to moderately risks. People with a salary of 25,000 to 50,000, on the other hand, tend to take significantly greater risks.

Borrower APR based on Loan Original Amount¶

Obviously, the bigger the loan amount, the lower the APR.

For all Prosper Rating types, the relationship between borrower APR and Duration¶

As the term gets bigger, the APR rises in the low risk category, whereas in the high risk rating , the APR falls.

the relationship between the APR and the Debt-to-Income Ratio  (in Income Range = 1 to 25K¶

those with low incomes ranging from 1 to 25,000 chose larger debt with higher risks, resulting in increased debt-to-income ratio, which is why the borrower APR peaks at 0.36 .
